Happy Days is <i>filmed</i>
before a studio audience.

01:26.019 --> 01:28.010
Well, I just finished it.

01:33.393 --> 01:35.259
I got my summer job
application right here.

01:35.395 --> 01:37.489
Now, those greenbacks are gonna
start rolling in now.

01:37.631 --> 01:39.099
Yep, yes, sirree.

01:39.232 --> 01:40.291
Big deal.

01:40.434 --> 01:42.493
A bag boy at Fensick's Market.

01:42.636 --> 01:45.162
I bet you make manager
by the end of summer.

01:45.305 --> 01:46.329
No.

01:46.473 --> 01:48.771
Well, maybe head of cold cuts.

01:48.909 --> 01:50.604
I don't understand

01:50.744 --> 01:52.712
why you don't want to work
in the hardware store.

01:52.846 --> 01:55.907
I'll pay you $1.20 an hour
and that's my final offer.

01:57.384 --> 01:59.648
- No. Thanks, but no thanks, Dad.
- Why not?

01:59.786 --> 02:02.813
Because Lori Beth's going to be
a checker at Fensick's.

02:02.956 --> 02:03.889
Yeah, that's right.

02:04.024 --> 02:05.753
I'll pay you $1.30 an hour

02:05.892 --> 02:07.292
and that's my final offer.

02:08.461 --> 02:09.554
No, Dad, you see,

02:09.696 --> 02:11.721
Lori Beth and I are going
to be like the baboons.

02:13.467 --> 02:14.457
We've been studying about it

02:14.601 --> 02:15.693
in our cultural anthropology
course, see.

02:15.836 --> 02:17.736
It's really very simple.

02:17.871 --> 02:19.965
Baboons who have a mate,

02:20.107 --> 02:21.199
why, they're happy, you know?

02:21.341 --> 02:22.866
And-and their
productivity increases.

02:23.010 --> 02:25.171
But baboons with no mates...

02:25.312 --> 02:27.212
well, they're very sad.

02:27.347 --> 02:28.212
(doorbell rings)

02:28.348 --> 02:29.645
Oh, I'll get it.

02:29.783 --> 02:31.649
I'm going ape
listening to Richie.

02:31.785 --> 02:33.776
(laughs)

02:35.756 --> 02:37.747
- Hi, hi, hi, hi, hi.
- Hi, Al!

02:38.892 --> 02:41.293
Oh, boy.

02:41.428 --> 02:42.293
Yeah.

02:42.429 --> 02:44.591
Still raining out.

02:44.731 --> 02:47.758
Oh, what a nice family.

02:47.901 --> 02:50.268
Howard, were you able to find
your cumberbund?

02:50.404 --> 02:54.033
Al, I could not let you
be the Man of the Year

02:54.174 --> 02:57.041
for the Sons of Italy
without a cumberbund.

02:57.177 --> 02:58.508
Here you are.

02:58.645 --> 03:01.114
It fits me... it may be
a little small on you.

03:01.248 --> 03:03.148
Hmm?

03:03.283 --> 03:05.581
Perfect.

03:05.719 --> 03:09.018
Alfred, I'll bet
you'll look so handsome.

03:09.156 --> 03:10.555
Oh... (chuckles)

03:10.690 --> 03:12.420
It's going to be
a big night for me.

03:12.559 --> 03:13.720
Who's the lucky lady, Al?

03:13.860 --> 03:15.590
Yeah, who are you taking
to your banquet?

03:15.729 --> 03:18.425
Oh, wow, you know, I've been
so excited and so busy,

03:18.565 --> 03:20.397
I just forgot all about that.

03:20.534 --> 03:22.559
Yeah, you know,
it's quite an honor.

03:22.702 --> 03:23.795
Well, you deserve it.

03:23.937 --> 03:25.234
Oh, I suppose.

03:25.372 --> 03:26.396
Hey, thanks, guy.

03:26.540 --> 03:28.167
- My pleasure.
- Have a wonderful time.

03:28.308 --> 03:29.173
(chuckles)
Oh. Bye-bye, everybody.

03:29.309 --> 03:30.333
JOANIE:
Bye, Al.

03:30.477 --> 03:32.036
Well, I got the cumberbund.

03:32.179 --> 03:34.648
Now I got to borrow a tux.

03:37.717 --> 03:40.619
Isn't it nice that Alfred
is finally being recognized

03:40.754 --> 03:42.620
for all the work he does
for the community?

03:42.756 --> 03:45.191
Well, it's just a shame.

03:45.325 --> 03:46.816
Al's having his big moment

03:46.960 --> 03:48.394
and nobody there
to share it with him.

03:48.528 --> 03:49.825
And Al needs
somebody by his side

03:49.963 --> 03:51.226
when he collects that award.

03:51.364 --> 03:53.595
He'll have somebody
by his side-- the presenter.

03:53.733 --> 03:55.668
- Oh...
- Come on, Marion.

03:55.802 --> 03:57.429
Well, maybe Richard's right.

03:57.571 --> 04:00.597
Why don't we fix him up
with Constance Brooks?

04:00.740 --> 04:04.006
Constance Brooks
is 72 years old.

04:04.144 --> 04:07.739
But she's still
cute as a button.

04:08.782 --> 04:10.648
I could get him a date.

04:10.784 --> 04:12.775
- You fix somebody up?
- Yeah.

04:12.919 --> 04:14.478
Why don't you get, uh, Fonzie

04:14.621 --> 04:16.487
to look in his little
black book, ape man?

04:16.623 --> 04:18.317
Fonzie's black book?

04:18.458 --> 04:19.391
Yeah.

04:19.526 --> 04:20.857
You think Mr. Smooth here

04:20.994 --> 04:23.395
doesn't have a little old
black book of his own?

04:24.431 --> 04:26.092
Let's see.

04:26.233 --> 04:28.099
Chock-full
of choice numbers, too.

04:28.235 --> 04:29.327
(Joanie laughs)

04:29.469 --> 04:30.664
All right, right here on-on

04:30.804 --> 04:32.203
Milwaukee Journal.

04:32.339 --> 04:33.238
Uh, Miller's Cleaners.

04:33.373 --> 04:35.808
Uh... Mom?

04:36.810 --> 04:38.334
That-That's okay, Rich.

04:38.478 --> 04:40.606
Fonz'll be back tomorrow.

04:40.747 --> 04:42.112
Why don't you look
under "D" for Dad?

04:42.249 --> 04:44.615
(scornfully):
"D" for Dad...

04:44.751 --> 04:46.378
"D" for...

04:46.520 --> 04:48.317
Dad.

04:53.260 --> 04:55.251
(thunder crashes)

04:59.099 --> 05:00.225
Hey, Al.

05:00.367 --> 05:01.766
Hi, Rich.

05:01.902 --> 05:04.302
You look like you should
be on a can of sardines.

05:04.437 --> 05:06.963
Oh, well, yeah,
my mom got me this outfit.

05:07.107 --> 05:08.597
Oh, Al, I just wanted
to talk to you.

05:08.742 --> 05:09.675
It's about Saturday night.

05:09.809 --> 05:11.107
- And I...
- I can't talk, Rich.

05:11.244 --> 05:12.302
Busy, busy, busy-

05:12.445 --> 05:13.879
Well...

05:21.855 --> 05:22.913
Well, Rich, old man,

05:23.056 --> 05:24.785
we got our summer jobs...

05:24.925 --> 05:26.620
- Well...
-...working on the docks.

05:26.760 --> 05:29.786
Associate longshoremen.

05:34.501 --> 05:35.991
Give me a break.

05:36.136 --> 05:37.001
- No lie, Rich.
- Yeah.

05:37.137 --> 05:38.434
We start Saturday.

05:38.572 --> 05:40.403
We work weekends
till school's out.

05:40.540 --> 05:41.837
We're going to be real men.

05:41.975 --> 05:43.966
Hard guys.

05:45.712 --> 05:47.407
Yeah, hard guys.

05:47.547 --> 05:50.346
Ruddy complexions,
maybe even tattoos.

05:50.483 --> 05:52.952
You want us to put in
a good word for you, mate?

05:53.086 --> 05:55.077
You look like
a hearty lad, ha...

05:56.690 --> 05:59.125
Uh, I think I'm doing fine
with my job at Fensick's Market.

05:59.259 --> 06:00.784
- Go on.
-(laughs)

06:00.927 --> 06:02.918
Work in a market
all summer with Lori Beth...

06:03.063 --> 06:04.621
- Yeah. -...while Pots
and I ride the nets

06:04.764 --> 06:06.391
and cavort with
waterfront trollops?

06:06.533 --> 06:07.932
POTSIE:
Come on, Ralph.

06:08.068 --> 06:09.433
- Forget Rich.
- Right.

06:09.569 --> 06:11.094
Let's go down to the docks,
you know?

06:11.238 --> 06:13.604
Meet with our cronies,
spit in the gutter and swear.

06:13.740 --> 06:16.004
Nah, it's raining outside.

06:16.142 --> 06:17.439
Let's just swear.

06:17.577 --> 06:20.274
♪ Heave ho, heave ho... ♪

06:24.651 --> 06:26.779
Oh, Al, do you think
I could talk to you now?

06:26.920 --> 06:27.785
I'm sorry, Rich.

06:27.921 --> 06:28.820
Yeah, I-l know,
busy, busy, busy.

06:28.955 --> 06:30.616
Busy means business.

06:30.757 --> 06:32.748
All right, well...

